This paper is about deep convolutional neural networks for single image super-resolution, which is a topic related to computer vision (cs.CV). The paper proposes an unsupervised learning approach for modeling the real-world degradation process from high-resolution to low-resolution images, which involves the use of generative adversarial networks (GANs) and bidirectional structural consistency. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves experiments on both synthetic and real-world images, which suggests that it may also be relevant to multimedia (cs.MM) and graphics (cs.GR) sub-categories.
